<br>
It can be argued that the person's own body, once incarcerated, is the only thing they have left possession-wise. They can read your mail, check your packages, etc, because outgoing mail is, once given to the mail system, property of that system (not the postal system, that's the step after it goes through the prison itself), incoming packages are likewise property of that institution. So is the room. So is everything that is in that room (though there are laws about what a person can possess, possession of material objects in prison is a privilege).<br>
<br>
The intended use of the DNA is to keep on file and compare to other crimes. In order for this to not violate the 4th amendment, there would have to be credible suspicion linking the person from whom the DNA sample is taken to the crime. That I think is the crux of the argument in this particular case. The police cannot randomly go up to people anywhere and demand DNA samples to compare to crime scenes unless they have reasonable suspicion. Sure, they've already been found guilty of a crime, but that doesn't mean they are in any way reasonably linked to any number of other crimes. The sampling here goes on without impunity as a means to arouse suspicion, not act upon suspicion.<br>
<br>
But, at the core, I think it hinges specifically on the fact that your inalienable rights are maintained in prison, though often in the strictest interpretation. The government controls the outgoing letters (speech, amendment 1) in such a way as to prevent illegal activities from taking place. They do not, however, stop inmates from criticizing the government, speaking their mind in lawful manner, writing their senator, etc. They're also free to practice religion in ways that do not endanger others or themselves. The second amendment - well, they don't get guns, obviously, but the strictest view of the second amendment only guarantees the right to bear in a well-regulated militia. Amendment 3 doesn't particularly apply to anything that a prisoner would ever encounter, and neither, really does amendment 10. However, all of the others are held up, specifically those to do with self-incrimination, speedy trial, jury trial, etc. <br>
<br>
That all being said, that's what I'm <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>assuming</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would be the reasoning behind it. It certainly seems like the best logical leg they have to stand on, even if, in all practicality, it's dubious at best. We already keep a fingerprint database, how is DNA any different (except in the fact it's often far more incriminating)? Probably because the merits and application of DNA evidence is still a hot-spot of debate in many trials. <br>
<br>
I don't particularly agree with it, but I somewhat understand the reasoning.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wrinsylkenhand>Wrin Sylkenhand </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle> the fury</span><br>  Posts: 1165<br> <font color=#330000>(10/2/03 2:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=5>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How the hell is this an invasion of privacy?</span><hr size=1> One of the reasons for the law was because when there was a suspition of the criminal haveing commited another crime they were alowed to day no to giving a sample, and the prisons didn't want to be bothered to talk to the prisoner about it. <p>Wrin ~Benevolent princess of the Bouncy Grrlz
